2. Prerequisites

Before creating an EKS cluster, ensure the following are installed:

AWS CLI
kubectl
eksctl
AWS account with proper permissions
IAM user configured using aws configure


3. Install AWS CLI
Linux/macOS
curl "https://awscli.amazonaws.com/AWSCLIV2.pkg" -o "AWSCLIV2.pkg"
sudo installer -pkg AWSCLIV2.pkg -target /
Verify Installation
aws --version
4. Configure AWS Credentials
aws configure

Provide:

AWS Access Key ID
AWS Secret Access Key
Default region (e.g., ap-south-1)
Output format (json)


5. Install kubectl
Linux
curl -LO "https://dl.k8s.io/release/$(curl -L -s https://dl.k8s.io/release/stable.txt)/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl"
chmod +x kubectl
sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/
macOS
brew install kubectl
Verify
kubectl version --client

6. Install eksctl
Linux/macOS
brew install eksctl

or

curl --silent --location \
"https://github.com/weaveworks/eksctl/releases/latest/download/eksctl_$(uname -s)_amd64.tar.gz" \
| tar xz -C /tmp

sudo mv /tmp/eksctl /usr/local/bin
Verify
eksctl version

7. Create EKS Cluster
Basic Command
eksctl create cluster \
  --name my-cluster \
  --region ap-south-1 \
  --nodegroup-name workers \
  --node-type t3.medium \
  --nodes 2
Parameters Explained
Parameter	Description
--name	Cluster name
--region	AWS region
--nodegroup-name	Worker node group name
--node-type	EC2 instance type
--nodes	Number of worker nodes
Cluster Creation Time
Typically takes 15–20 minutes.


8. Verify Cluster Creation
eksctl get cluster
kubectl get nodes

Example Output:

NAME                                               STATUS   ROLES    AGE   VERSION
ip-192-168-10-10.ap-south-1.compute.internal       Ready    <none>   5m    v1.31
ip-192-168-20-20.ap-south-1.compute.internal       Ready    <none>   5m    v1.31


9. Update kubeconfig to Access EKS Cluster

If kubeconfig is not configured automatically:

aws eks update-kubeconfig \
  --region ap-south-1 \
  --name my-cluster

This command updates:

~/.kube/config

10. Test Cluster Access

kubectl get nodes
kubectl get namespaces
kubectl cluster-info


11. What is a Pod?

A Pod is the smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes.

A Pod can contain:

One container
Multiple containers sharing the same:
Network namespace
Storage volumes
Pod Characteristics
Gets a unique IP address.
Containers inside the pod communicate using localhost.
Pods are ephemeral (can be recreated).


