16. Introduction to Service

A Service provides a stable network endpoint to access Pods.

Without a Service:

Pod IPs change whenever Pods are recreated.

With a Service:

Stable DNS name
Stable IP address
Load balancing across multiple Pods


17. Types of Services
Type	Description
ClusterIP	Internal access only (default)
NodePort	Accessible through worker node IP and port
LoadBalancer	Creates AWS ELB automatically
ExternalName	Maps to an external DNS name


18. Create First Pod Using kubectl run
kubectl run my-nginx \
  --image=nginx \
  --port=80

Verify:

kubectl get pods
kubectl describe pod my-nginx

Expected Output:

NAME       READY   STATUS    RESTARTS   AGE
my-nginx   1/1     Running   0          20s


19. View Pod Logs
kubectl logs my-nginx

20. Execute Commands Inside Pod
kubectl exec -it my-nginx -- bash

If bash is unavailable:

kubectl exec -it my-nginx -- sh

21. Expose Pod Using kubectl expose
Create ClusterIP Service
kubectl expose pod my-nginx \
  --port=80 \
  --target-port=80 \
  --type=ClusterIP \
  --name=my-nginx-service

Verify:

kubectl get svc

22. Expose Pod as LoadBalancer (Recommended in EKS)
kubectl expose pod my-nginx \
  --port=80 \
  --target-port=80 \
  --type=LoadBalancer \
  --name=my-nginx-lb




24. Complete Practical Workflow
Step 1: Create Cluster
eksctl create cluster \
  --name demo-cluster \
  --region ap-south-1 \
  --nodes 2
Step 2: Verify Nodes
kubectl get nodes
Step 3: Create Pod
kubectl run my-nginx --image=nginx
Step 4: Verify Pod
kubectl get pods
Step 5: Expose Pod
kubectl expose pod my-nginx \
  --port=80 \
  --type=LoadBalancer
Step 6: Get Load Balancer URL
kubectl get svc
Step 7: Open Browser
http://<EXTERNAL-IP>
25. Delete Pod
kubectl delete pod my-nginx
26. Delete Service
kubectl delete svc my-nginx
27. Delete EKS Cluster
eksctl delete cluster \
  --name demo-cluster \
  --region ap-south-1
28. Important kubectl Commands
Command	Purpose
kubectl get pods	List pods
kubectl get svc	List services
kubectl get nodes	List worker nodes
kubectl describe pod <name>	Pod details
kubectl logs <pod>	Show logs
kubectl exec -it <pod> -- sh	Open shell
kubectl delete pod <name>	Delete pod
29. Real-World Example

Suppose you deploy an Nginx pod in EKS:

Pod runs the Nginx container.
Service of type LoadBalancer creates AWS ELB.
ELB provides a public DNS name.
Users access the application using the ELB DNS.
